WEBVTT

00:01.330 --> 00:05.699
(xylophone playing softly)

00:39.370 --> 00:41.395
DEEJAY:
You've been listening
to Carl Orff's

00:41.440 --> 00:43.567
"Vier Stucke fur Xylophon."

00:43.610 --> 00:47.102
Xylophones and pan flutes
are healing instruments

00:47.140 --> 00:50.075
best played as a detox
from the intensity of the clay.

00:50.110 --> 00:51.247
Shut up.

00:51.280 --> 00:53.612
(sighs)

01:03.490 --> 01:05.481
No.

01:23.380 --> 01:26.144
(chuckles)

01:26.180 --> 01:27.442
Elsbeth, I'm going into court.

01:27.480 --> 01:29.118
It's too late to change
trial strategy.

01:29.150 --> 01:31.311
You can't win
by fighting sexism.

01:31.350 --> 01:35.116
They're charging sexism. Are you
saying I can't refute it?

01:35.160 --> 01:36.457
No. Yes.

01:36.490 --> 01:39.493
I mean the plaintiff
has a broken iPhone.

01:40.530 --> 01:43.522
Okay. And why is that important?

01:43.570 --> 01:44.821
Because her office
sent over files

01:44.870 --> 01:46.394
with ﬁve different buck slips.

01:46.440 --> 01:48.237
Five different assistants.

01:48.270 --> 01:49.532
RAYNA:
Mr. Napier, hello.

01:49.570 --> 01:52.471
This is my law partner,
Elsbeth Tascioni.

01:52.510 --> 01:54.603
She'll be my
second chair today.
That's my general counsel.

01:54.640 --> 01:56.244
He's advising me to settle,
Ms. Hecht.

01:56.280 --> 01:58.498
ELSBETH:
Oh, no. You can't.

01:58.550 --> 02:01.314
Our worry is the makeup of the
plaintiff's team. We've looked

02:01.350 --> 02:03.545
at their wins and losses...
That just makes them
overconfident.

02:03.590 --> 02:05.615
Just give us today.

02:05.650 --> 02:07.379
Then we can decide
whether to settle.
Okay, I have business

02:07.420 --> 02:08.887
with the governor's office,
and their lead attorney

02:08.920 --> 02:09.887
is the governor's wife.

02:09.930 --> 02:12.592
What?!

02:12.630 --> 02:14.222
Alicia!

02:14.260 --> 02:16.569
I didn't know you were on this.

02:16.600 --> 02:18.158
I didn't know either.

02:18.200 --> 02:20.168
But I guess I am.

02:20.200 --> 02:21.736
Hi.

02:21.770 --> 02:24.466
Hi.

02:25.510 --> 02:26.772
Who's that?

02:26.810 --> 02:28.630
Elsbeth Tascioni.

02:28.680 --> 02:30.341
Is she good?

02:30.380 --> 02:31.870
Yep.

02:31.910 --> 02:33.741
Well, I like the talent pool
at J-Serve.

02:33.780 --> 02:38.240
I also believe that there aren't
enough women CEOs

02:38.290 --> 02:40.508
in the tech business.
So when they approached me,

02:40.560 --> 02:42.653
I said yes.
And in the three years

02:42.690 --> 02:44.885
you served as CEO at J-Serve,
what happened

02:44.930 --> 02:47.319
to the share price?
It doubled.

02:47.360 --> 02:49.897
DEAN: So, uh, despite this
unprecedented success

02:49.930 --> 02:52.660
and a mere two weeks
before your options vested,

02:52.700 --> 02:54.964
you were
unceremoniously terminated?

02:55.000 --> 02:56.900
RAYNA: Objection,
Your Honor,

02:56.940 --> 02:58.931
to "unprecedented success."
Calls for a conclusion.

02:58.970 --> 03:00.904
That it does. Sustained.

03:00.940 --> 03:02.874
Were you given any reason
for your firing?

03:02.910 --> 03:05.708
Mr. Napier told me
that my brash management style

03:05.750 --> 03:07.968
_ was inconsistent
With the company's culture.

03:08.020 --> 03:10.409
DEAN:
So you're suing them.
Yes.

03:10.450 --> 03:12.759
They fired me
because I'm a woman.

03:12.790 --> 03:14.815
And they can't do that.

03:14.860 --> 03:16.680
DEAN:
Thank you.

03:19.030 --> 03:23.228
Ms. Vargas, how would you
describe your relationship

03:23.270 --> 03:24.897
with your subordinates?

03:24.930 --> 03:26.761
How would I desc...

03:26.800 --> 03:27.994
I-I don't know, um... effective.

03:28.040 --> 03:29.667
Ms. Vargas,

03:29.710 --> 03:31.530
how many aides have you had
in the last two months?

03:31.570 --> 03:33.777
Objection, Your Honor.
Relevance.

03:33.810 --> 03:35.937
Ms. Vargas claims that she was
fired due to sexism.

03:35.980 --> 03:37.004
We_ believe there's_ a
far Simpler explanation.

03:37.050 --> 03:39.006
I guess I will...

03:39.050 --> 03:41.018
No, I know I
will overrule.

03:41.050 --> 03:43.314
Ms. Vargas, how many aides?

03:43.350 --> 03:45.318
I don't know. Five.

03:45.350 --> 03:47.386
Five assistants
in the last two months?

03:47.420 --> 03:49.012
It's very hard
to find good help.

03:49.060 --> 03:50.687
(scoffs, snorts)

03:50.730 --> 03:53.028
Your Honor,
please ask the defense

03:53.060 --> 03:55.392
to_ restrain itself.
Restraln yourself, ma'am.

03:55.430 --> 03:56.419
RAYNA:
Ms. Vargas,

03:56.470 --> 03:58.426
have you thrown your cell phone

03:58.470 --> 04:00.768
at your assistants?
ALICIA:
Objection, Your Honor.

04:00.800 --> 04:03.030
ELSBETH and RAYNA:
Goes to management skills.

04:03.070 --> 04:05.709
Yes. Overruled.

04:05.740 --> 04:06.877
You may answer, ma'am.

04:06.910 --> 04:08.400
Look, women
are called bitches

04:08.440 --> 04:10.340
when they have
a tough management style.

04:10.380 --> 04:13.679
I admit I have
a tough management style,

04:13.720 --> 04:15.779
but I am fair.

04:15.820 --> 04:17.549
That was a good
pivot on their part.

04:17.590 --> 04:19.558
Yep, it's no longer
about sexism.

04:19.590 --> 04:21.410
It's about our client
being a bitch.

04:21.460 --> 04:24.349
So we make it about
the CEO before her.

04:24.390 --> 04:26.028
Compare their behavior.

04:26.060 --> 04:29.666
Yeah, he's the same
and they didn't fire him.

04:29.700 --> 04:31.827
Diane, you knew the CEO before
Camilla. What was his name?

04:31.870 --> 04:34.031
Um, Everett Tatum.

04:34.070 --> 04:37.836
Wasn't there a sexual harassment
swt against hIm?
There was.

04:37.870 --> 04:39.838
I'll e-mail it to you.

04:59.400 --> 05:00.992
VVhoa!

05:01.030 --> 05:02.054
What?!

05:02.100 --> 05:03.089
(groans)

05:03.130 --> 05:05.098
Computers are down.
Who did it?

05:05.130 --> 05:07.360
What happened?
What's going on here?

05:07.400 --> 05:09.038
Dean, Alicia.

05:11.840 --> 05:14.070
"Wire a payment of $50,000

05:14.110 --> 05:16.704
"to the following account number
within 72 hours

05:16.750 --> 05:19.617
"or the decryption key will be
destroyed and your files

05:19.650 --> 05:22.448
permanently lost."
(groans)
Ransomware.

05:22.490 --> 05:24.708
It was an e-mail from Alicia.
I just clicked on it.

05:24.750 --> 05:26.456
I-I didn't send you anything.

05:26.490 --> 05:29.823
(groans)

05:29.860 --> 05:31.987
I just lost my deposition...!
MAN: Need some help here!

05:32.030 --> 05:33.395
WOMAN:
My computer's frozen!

05:33.430 --> 05:36.558
This isn't good.

05:36.600 --> 05:38.693
It's everything.
All our backup files,

05:38.730 --> 05:40.698
all our accounts.
Everything's lost.
DEAN: We're due in court

05:40.740 --> 05:42.708
in an hour and we can't
get our trIal notes.

05:42.740 --> 05:44.002
What happens if we don't pay?
CAREY:
Everything gets deleted

05:44.040 --> 05:45.860
in 72 hours.
71 hours.

05:45.910 --> 05:47.571
It's on our laptops, too?

05:47.610 --> 05:49.646
Everything's
on the same network.
That's insane.

05:49.680 --> 05:52.569
This is like modern day piracy.
Where's Cary?
Here.

05:52.620 --> 05:54.110
No, Agos, Cary.
Uh, he's at lunch.

05:54.150 --> 05:55.674
I'll conference him in.

05:56.690 --> 05:59.579
(phone ringing)

05:59.620 --> 06:03.056
It's your phone.
Yep.

06:03.090 --> 06:04.785
Uh...

06:04.830 --> 06:06.752
They know I'm at lunch.
It can't be good news.

06:06.800 --> 06:08.654
Well, maybe they're dropping
the charges against you.

06:10.500 --> 06:12.388
It's Cary.

06:12.440 --> 06:13.361
ALICIA:
Cary, we've had

06:13.400 --> 06:15.664
a malware attack.
All our computers are down.

06:15.700 --> 06:17.463
They're asking
for $50,000

06:17.510 --> 06:21.139
or we lose all our files
In 71 hours.
What?

06:21.180 --> 06:22.329
Wait, we need to
loop Kalinda in.

06:22.380 --> 06:24.644
They're calling you, they're
calling... they're calling you.

06:24.680 --> 06:25.647
(phone ringing)
Mute your phone.

06:25.680 --> 06:28.069
Where is it?
I don't know.

06:28.120 --> 06:31.715
(ringing continues)

06:31.750 --> 06:33.786
What about the backup files?

06:33.820 --> 06:35.788
Oh, yeah.
We can restore from backup.

06:35.820 --> 06:37.788
Hi. This is Kalinda.
DIANE:
Kalinda, it's me.

06:37.830 --> 06:39.752
I inadvertently downloaded
a virus.

06:39.800 --> 06:41.825
The instructions say we need

06:41.860 --> 06:43.794
to make a payment
of $50,000.

06:43.830 --> 06:46.094
And we don't have a backup.
What do you mean we
don't have any backup?

06:46.130 --> 06:48.132
We were contracting
for an outside I.T. redesign,

06:48.170 --> 06:50.764
but we had to use the money
for... something else.

06:50.810 --> 06:52.698
My bail.

06:52.740 --> 06:54.469
Look, what's the time frame?

06:54.510 --> 06:56.137
DIANE:
71 hours.

06:56.180 --> 06:58.808
Okay, I'll look into it.
ALICIA:
We don't have time.

06:58.850 --> 07:00.818
We're in court.
They are holding
our case files ransom.

07:00.850 --> 07:02.738
We have to pay.

07:02.790 --> 07:04.917
$50,000? Seriously?
We don't_have
any option,

07:04.950 --> 07:06.884
all right? It's our files...

07:06.920 --> 07:08.979
We could contact
the authorities.
And then what?

07:09.020 --> 07:10.988
The investigation leaks
and the whole legal community

07:11.030 --> 07:13.624
knows we're vulnerable.
DEAN:
Clients will leave.

07:13.660 --> 07:15.753
Camilla could even sue us
if she thinks this impacts

07:15.800 --> 07:17.529
her representation.
ALICIA:
Which it might.

07:17.570 --> 07:18.867
DEAN:
I'm with Alicia.

07:18.900 --> 07:20.697
We need to pay up.
Kalinda,

07:20.740 --> 07:21.832
is there anything to do?
Look, I don't like

07:21.870 --> 07:24.703
funding a criminal operation.
I know. And if this were

07:24.740 --> 07:26.537
Lockhart/Gardner,
we would have other options.

07:26.580 --> 07:27.774
I just don't see any.

07:27.810 --> 07:30.699
Where does the $50,000
come from?
All of us.

07:30.750 --> 07:32.718
All of the partners,
$5,000 each in two hours.

07:32.750 --> 07:33.717
I agree with Diane.

07:33.750 --> 07:36.913
(phone rings)
(others murmuring, protesting)

07:36.950 --> 07:38.713
Finn, hi.

07:38.750 --> 07:39.717
Wow, you sound anxious.

07:39.760 --> 07:40.909
Yeah.

07:40.960 --> 07:42.780
Firm politics.
So I considered it

07:42.830 --> 07:44.889
carefully and I'd be honored

07:44.930 --> 07:46.727
to offer a few remarks
on your behalf

07:46.760 --> 07:48.648
when you announce
your candidacy.
Are you sure?

07:48.700 --> 07:50.861
Uh, that won't hurt you there?
I don't know.

07:50.900 --> 07:52.265
I'm not sure of anything
these days.

07:52.300 --> 07:54.564
I like living on the edge.

07:54.600 --> 07:56.830
(chuckles)
Me, too.

07:56.870 --> 07:58.906
IfI fall, you'll catch me?
No, I'll be plummeting with you.

07:58.940 --> 08:00.601
ALICIA: Who was
your chief executive officer

08:00.640 --> 08:02.574
before Camilla?

08:02.610 --> 08:03.907
Everett Tatum,

08:03.950 --> 08:05.008
a very capable
executive.

08:05.050 --> 08:06.870
You didn't fire Mr. Tatum,
did you?

08:06.920 --> 08:08.876
No, there was no reason to.
Because his brash

08:08.920 --> 08:11.889
management style didn't clash
with the company's culture?

08:11.920 --> 08:14.889
Well, he didn't make us
vulnerable to a lawsuit.

08:14.920 --> 08:16.888
They're going after equivalence.
This is

08:16.930 --> 08:17.885
an employee complaint

08:17.930 --> 08:19.818
_ filed
against Everett Tatum

08:19.860 --> 08:22.226
for sexual harassment.
Have you seen this?

08:22.260 --> 08:23.522
No.

08:23.570 --> 08:25.060
You were CC'd there.

08:25.100 --> 08:26.294
Do you see?

08:26.330 --> 08:28.935
Mr. Tatum
wasn't fired,

08:28.970 --> 08:30.062
was he?
No.

08:30.110 --> 08:33.238
In fact, two months after
this incident, you offered him

08:33.280 --> 08:34.872
a 20% raise, didn't you?

08:34.910 --> 08:36.901
So a white male

08:36.950 --> 08:38.872
is rewarded for
the same behavior that...

08:38.910 --> 08:39.740
Objection, Your Honor.
What is she
objecting to?

08:39.780 --> 08:41.179
I haven't finished
the question yet.

08:41.220 --> 08:42.244
Go ahead.

08:42.280 --> 08:43.918
A white male is rewarded

08:43.950 --> 08:45.884
for the same behavior

08:45.920 --> 08:47.911
that leads to a woman's firing.

08:47.960 --> 08:50.258
Objection.
I'll withdraw.

08:50.290 --> 08:52.952
Thank you, sir.

08:53.000 --> 08:53.955
(whispering)

08:54.000 --> 08:56.924
(groans)
Now what?

08:56.970 --> 08:58.892
ALICIA: I can't even
begin to guess.

08:58.930 --> 09:00.898
Mr. Napier,

09:00.940 --> 09:03.829
isn't it true
that Mr. Everett's...

09:03.870 --> 09:06.338
Excuse me.
What was his last name?

09:06.370 --> 09:07.598
The previous CEO?

09:07.640 --> 09:08.971
Mr. Tatum.
Right.

09:09.010 --> 09:11.877
Isn't it true
that whatever he did,

09:11.910 --> 09:13.912
you became concerned
about the next CEO

09:13.950 --> 09:15.975
repeating that behavior?

09:16.020 --> 09:17.681
NAPIER:
I'm sorry, what?

09:17.720 --> 09:19.688
Well, the defense
is trying to suggest

09:19.720 --> 09:22.985
_ there_ was sexism_
in your firing of Camilla.

09:23.030 --> 09:25.123
I like that brooch.

09:25.160 --> 09:27.993
They're suggesting there
was sexism in firing her

09:28.030 --> 09:31.796
and not firing the male CEO
for the exact same actions.

09:31.830 --> 09:35.937
Didn't the misbehavior
of the Mr. Other CEO Guy

09:35.970 --> 09:39.007
just sensitize you
to not letting Camilla do

09:39.040 --> 09:40.837
the same thing and encourage you
to say, "Never again"?

09:40.880 --> 09:42.370
ALICIA:
Objection.

09:42.410 --> 09:44.970
That is the definition
of leading.

09:45.010 --> 09:46.944
Yes. I will sustain that.

09:46.980 --> 09:49.847
So, why did you fire Camilla?

09:49.890 --> 09:50.982
Well...

09:51.020 --> 09:53.853
because we said, "Never again."

09:53.890 --> 09:55.357
ELSBETH:
Thank you, sir.

09:55.390 --> 09:57.085
We need to take her out.

10:15.440 --> 10:16.976
And just like that,

10:17.010 --> 10:20.241
we turn $50,000 in cash
into zeroes and ones.

10:20.280 --> 10:22.919
Who knew Bitcoin would
come in so handy?

10:22.950 --> 10:24.087
How are you entering it?

10:24.120 --> 10:28.056
I type in my nine-digit
routing number

10:28.090 --> 10:31.253
and they e-mail me
the decryption key.

10:31.290 --> 10:33.019
Okay.

10:35.300 --> 10:36.927
How long do we wait?
I don't know.

10:36.970 --> 10:38.961
It says simultaneously.

10:41.200 --> 10:43.065
Something's wrong.
DIANE:
So what do we do?

10:43.110 --> 10:46.034
Bottom of the page,
there's a helpline number.

10:46.070 --> 10:47.071
DIANE:
There's a helpline

10:47.110 --> 10:49.169
for ransomware?
That's helpful

10:49.210 --> 10:50.279
of the criminals.

10:53.850 --> 10:54.874
MAN (recorded):
Thank you for calling

10:54.920 --> 10:56.171
the Trojanlock help desk.

10:56.220 --> 10:59.041
At present, we are assisting
other customers.

10:59.090 --> 11:01.888
Please have your routing number
ready, and you will be assisted

11:01.920 --> 11:03.353
in the order you called.
DIANE: Amazing.

11:03.390 --> 11:05.927
Uh, Kalinda...

11:05.960 --> 11:07.359
see what you can do.

11:07.400 --> 11:10.267
Okay.

11:10.300 --> 11:13.929
Okay.
I've re-tabbed the depo
testimony for the rest

11:13.970 --> 11:17.337
of our cross-exams.
Wow, this must have
been what it was like

11:17.370 --> 11:20.009
to practice law
before computers.
Yup.

11:20.040 --> 11:22.941
So, Camilla-- she really
fired five of her assistants?

11:22.980 --> 11:24.470
I can say this
because I'm a woman,

11:24.510 --> 11:26.341
but she's probably
a bitch on wheels.

11:26.380 --> 11:28.871
But her behavior wouldn't
even be a talking point

11:28.920 --> 11:30.182
if she were a man.

11:30.220 --> 11:32.381
Do you really want to
compare experiences of bias?

11:32.420 --> 11:35.116
Tascioni-- what are
we gonna do about her?

11:35.160 --> 11:36.218
She's killing us.

11:38.060 --> 11:39.425
What?

11:45.230 --> 11:47.369
Alicia...
why aren't you

11:47.400 --> 11:50.301
answering your e-mails?
Eli, I'm working.
Can we do this another time?

11:50.340 --> 11:53.036
"Thank you very much, Peter,
for that warm introduction.

11:53.080 --> 11:54.229
"I hope you don't
think I'll go easy

11:54.280 --> 11:56.134
on your administration now."

11:56.180 --> 11:59.047
It was a joke, Eli.
That's all.

11:59.080 --> 12:01.071
"I'd also like
to thank ASA Polmar

12:01.120 --> 12:03.145
for saying such nice words."

12:03.190 --> 12:05.112
Yes.

12:05.150 --> 12:07.015
What?
He's introducing you?

12:07.060 --> 12:09.051
Finn is?
Yes.

12:09.090 --> 12:11.979
No, he isn't.
Yes, he said he would.

12:12.030 --> 12:12.997
Well, of course
he said he would.

12:13.030 --> 12:14.099
It puts him on the world stage.

12:14.130 --> 12:16.098
Eli, obviously
this matters to you

12:16.130 --> 12:18.291
because you're here,
but for the life of me,

12:18.330 --> 12:20.491
I can't figure out
what your problem is.
You have the governor

12:20.540 --> 12:23.134
of the great state of
Illinois introducing you.

12:23.170 --> 12:25.161
Then you have an ASA
from a tiny division

12:25.210 --> 12:26.507
of the state's attorney's
office introducing you, too?

12:26.540 --> 12:29.270
He's a hero, Eli.
He was shot in the line of duty.

12:29.310 --> 12:32.006
And he works under
my opponent Castro.

12:32.050 --> 12:34.041
Elfman thinks it looks good
that he endorsed me.

12:34.080 --> 12:36.116
Then tell Fin_n he can endorse
you at an inner-City event

12:36.150 --> 12:38.186
with 20 people at some
stinlq high school gym,

12:38.220 --> 12:39.448
not in front of
the national press.

12:39.490 --> 12:41.287
What national press?
This is an event,

12:41.320 --> 12:44.187
Alicia... uh, uh, maybe you're
not reading your own press.

12:44.230 --> 12:46.425
People like this story.
They're paying attention.

12:46.460 --> 12:49.327
You're the new power couple
from Obama's home state.

12:49.360 --> 12:51.123
It's broken through
to the MSM.

12:51.170 --> 12:53.263
Oh, don't say "MSM," please.

12:53.300 --> 12:55.461
Tell Finn he has been
disinvited.

12:55.500 --> 12:57.502
I can't do that.
Yes, you can.
You're running for office.

12:57.540 --> 12:59.360
You can do whatever you like.
Why are all the computers

12:59.410 --> 13:01.105
here counting down? I feel like
I'm in a Bruckheimer movie.

13:01.140 --> 13:02.437
Wait, if I don't disinvite

13:02.480 --> 13:05.199
Finn... Peter won't come?
Peter has the

13:05.250 --> 13:06.069
governor's conference.

13:06.110 --> 13:07.509
He has
allotted time to endorse you.

13:07.550 --> 13:09.211
He wants to endorse you,
he does not

13:09.250 --> 13:11.184
want to share the stage
with an ASA.

13:11.220 --> 13:14.087
So he won't come? Seriously?

13:14.120 --> 13:15.519
Tell Finn he can

13:15.560 --> 13:18.085
endorse you at a later event.

13:18.130 --> 13:19.222
You need Peter.

13:19.260 --> 13:21.251
You do not need Finn.

13:30.640 --> 13:32.198
Hi.

13:32.240 --> 13:34.105
Thanks for seeing me.

13:34.140 --> 13:35.209
No problem.

13:35.240 --> 13:37.401
So, you're moving up
in the world.

13:37.450 --> 13:39.179
What do you want, Kalinda?

13:39.210 --> 13:41.144
Oh, just to say hello.

13:41.180 --> 13:43.284
No. What do you want?

13:43.320 --> 13:45.845
My firm has been hit
by ransomware.

13:45.890 --> 13:47.619
It's called Trojanlock.

13:47.660 --> 13:50.083
We paid the ransom, but they
didn't send the decryption key.

13:50.130 --> 13:52.155
Hmm. Tough break.
The account number
I wired it to--

13:52.190 --> 13:53.396
can you trace it?

13:53.430 --> 13:54.988
With a warrant.

13:55.030 --> 13:57.464
I only have 45 hours.
Oh, that's too bad.

13:57.500 --> 13:59.388
It'll take 48 hours
to get a warrant.

13:59.430 --> 14:02.035
Okay. Thanks.

14:03.940 --> 14:07.876
I don't like that I only see you
when you need something.

14:11.380 --> 14:12.642
Look, I don't
like it either.

14:12.680 --> 14:15.410
Then... stop it.

14:16.950 --> 14:18.349
How have you been?

14:18.390 --> 14:19.948
(wry laugh)

14:19.990 --> 14:21.514
I'll call you.

14:21.560 --> 14:23.187
Am I being dismissed?

14:23.230 --> 14:25.448
You're being dismissed.

14:27.300 --> 14:29.894
(jaunty Muzak playing
over phone)

14:29.930 --> 14:33.297
(slow dripping)

14:46.980 --> 14:48.379
Hello, my name is Bruce.

14:48.420 --> 14:50.308
Thank you for holding.
May I help you?

14:50.350 --> 14:53.558
Uh, yes.
I made a $50,000 payment

14:53.590 --> 14:56.980
and I'm still awaiting an e-mail
with a decryption key.

14:57.030 --> 14:58.622
Let me check
on your order status.

14:58.660 --> 15:00.457
(dripping continues)

15:00.500 --> 15:02.297
Yes, here we are.

15:02.330 --> 15:04.025
As requested,
that decryption key

15:04.070 --> 15:06.459
was e-mailed to "dlockhart
@lockhartandgardner.com."

15:06.500 --> 15:08.036
Oh, no, it...

15:08.070 --> 15:10.004
Oh.

15:10.040 --> 15:12.201
I think when
I filled out the form,

15:12.240 --> 15:13.969
it auto-filled
with my old e-mail address.

15:14.010 --> 15:15.671
I need the key sent
to my new address.

15:15.710 --> 15:17.678
I'm so sorry,

15:17.710 --> 15:20.440
I'm afraid we're only permitted
to send the decryption key

15:22.720 --> 15:24.608
You're kidding. You're-You're
ransoming my business

15:24.650 --> 15:26.311
and this is where
you draw the line?

15:26.350 --> 15:27.715
Will there be
anything else, ma'am?

15:27.760 --> 15:30.649
Uh, yes. I would like to
speak to the supervisor.

15:30.690 --> 15:32.624
It went to Lockhart/Gardner.

15:32.660 --> 15:34.491
Oh, dear God, this
is like a nightmare.

15:34.530 --> 15:36.225
We need to call them.

15:36.260 --> 15:38.524
Are you serious?
(stammers)

15:40.270 --> 15:42.261
(phone rings)

15:43.370 --> 15:44.530
David Lee.

15:44.570 --> 15:46.162
(softly clears throat)

15:46.210 --> 15:48.576
Hello, David.
It's Diane.

15:48.610 --> 15:51.078
Ah, Diane.
Forget something on the way out,

15:51.110 --> 15:52.407
like the silverware?

15:52.450 --> 15:55.169
David, I, um...

15:55.220 --> 15:57.211
I'm awaiting an important e-mail

15:57.250 --> 16:00.356
that was inadvertently
sent to my L.G.

16:00.390 --> 16:03.553
e-mail address, and I need you
to do me the courtesy

16:03.590 --> 16:05.581
of forwarding it.
Certainly,

16:05.630 --> 16:07.996
just as soon as monkeys
fly out of my butt.

16:09.030 --> 16:11.260
Well, that was fairly crass.

16:11.300 --> 16:13.734
I've been holding it back
all these years.

16:13.770 --> 16:15.567
Nice talking to you, Diane.

16:15.600 --> 16:16.737
Uh, D-David, wait.

16:16.770 --> 16:18.761
What do you want?

16:18.810 --> 16:20.778
What do I want?

16:20.810 --> 16:22.437
Two clients.

16:22.480 --> 16:24.402
No.
Tell you what,

16:24.450 --> 16:26.748
why don't you come over
and prostrate yourself

16:26.780 --> 16:29.340
and maybe we'll work
something out.

16:33.560 --> 16:35.255
Can we at least get
a bucket in here?

16:35.290 --> 16:36.518
Dana Lee

16:36.560 --> 16:38.528
Boykin. I was
a flight attendant

16:38.560 --> 16:40.221
on Azo Charter.
And this

16:40.260 --> 16:42.694
is a private jet line
that serves Mr. Napier?

16:42.730 --> 16:44.459
_ Yes.
Did you ever overhear
a conversation

16:44.500 --> 16:46.525
between Mr. Napier
and the plaintiff?

16:46.570 --> 16:48.299
